      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for volume-averaged shear stress < 5% on the fine grid; Richardson extrapolation applied across three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three meshes (2.1M, 5.8M, 14.2M cells) were generated with uniform refinement ratio r = 1.35. GCI on the fine grid for volume-averaged shear stress was 2.8%, below the 5% threshold. Apparent order of convergence p = 1.94, consistent with second-order spatial discretisation. Required Level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity and density) match CFD boundary conditions within ±5%.",
      "rationale": "PIV experiments were conducted with a blood-analogue fluid (40% glycerol–water, μ = 3.2 mPa·s, ρ = 1060 kg/m³). Pump speed was controlled to ±10 RPM; flow rate to ±0.05 L/min. All deviations from nominal boundary conditions were within ±3%, satisfying the ±5% criterion. Required Level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (R² or normalised RMSE) between simulated and measured output quantity ≥ 0.90 or ≤ 0.10 respectively, across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Pooled Pearson R² = 0.923 for scalar shear-stress magnitude across all five operating points and 1,240 spatial locations, exceeding the 0.90 threshold. MAE = 4.7 Pa, below 10 Pa acceptance criterion. The output comparison factor is assessed as meeting Required Level 2. Note: the metric captures scalar magnitude agreement but does not directly assess whether the model correctly identifies the worst-case operating condition among the five combinations, which is the primary COU question. The team considered this distinction immaterial given the high R² value."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validated quantity (shear-stress field) is mechanistically linked to the COU quantity of interest (relative hemolysis index RH) via a documented power-law hemolysis model.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model (ΔHb/Hb = C·τ^α·t^β) directly maps shear stress magnitude and exposure time to hemolysis index. Shear-stress magnitude is therefore the primary mechanical driver of RH. The team concluded that validating the shear-stress field is equivalent to validating the hemolysis prediction, without separately assessing whether the model correctly rank-orders operating conditions by RH. Required Level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
